Actually, the simplest approach: just make the render function dynamic. Since the Overlay only has title as a constructor arg, I can only set it once. But I can work around this by passing the title through the component or through a footer.

OR... I can make the body component also render a "header" with the current phase name. That way even if the Overlay title doesn't update, the body shows the current phase.

Hmm, this is getting hacky. Let me take a step back.

The real fix the user wants: no scroll reset on keypress, and the animation timer not resetting. The scroll reset happens because `tui.requestRender()` is called. But `requestRender()` is necessary to update the display on input. So the scroll issue is about the frequency of re-renders, not the overlay reconstruction.

Actually wait - does `requestRender` cause scroll reset? Earlier I established that the widget re-renders on interaction and doesn't cause scroll issues. So `requestRender()` alone doesn't reset scroll. The issue with the OLD code was the 60ms timer calling `setWorkingIndicator` which forced full TUI repaints.

So actually, `rebuild()` calling `tui.requestRender()` on input is fine - it's a single re-render in response to user interaction, not a timer-driven one.

The main fix needed: stop creating a new Overlay on every keypress (which resets animStart). Instead, just requestRender and let the existing overlay components update their state.

So the fix is simpler than I thought:
1. Create ONE overlay with a static bodyComponent that reads from mutable state vars
2. On input, update state vars and call `tui.requestRender()`
3. The bodyComponent.render() reads the latest state vars and builds/renders the appropriate content

For the title, I can update it by... hmm, the Overlay doesn't support title changes. So either:
- Use a static title ("Phase Detail")
- Or access the private title field (bad practice)
- Or include the phase name in the body

Let me just use a static title. "Phase Detail" works. The body already shows the phase name.

Let me implement this now.

